Alternatively, note that `(x, y, z) = (n, n, n)` gives `4n³ = 3n² * n`, which is false unless `n = 0`, but perhaps `(n-1, n, n(n-1))` for `n > 1`? 

But this seems too ad-hoc.

Alternatively, perhaps setting `x = 1`, `y = 1`, and solving for `z` as `4z = n(1 + 2z)` → `4z = n + 2nz` → `z(4 - 2n) = n`. 

This only works if `4 - 2n` divides `n`. If `n = 2`, `0 = 2`, no solution.
